📘 Subject: General Studies Paper I (Prelims – Polity)
🧠 Topic: Judiciary – Supreme Court of India

(Very important topic for both Prelims & Mains.)

1️⃣ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)
🔹 What is the Supreme Court?

The Supreme Court of India is:

Highest judicial authority
Guardian of the Constitution
Protector of Fundamental Rights

📌 Mentioned in Articles 124–147

🔵 Composition
Chief Justice of India (CJI)
Other judges (maximum 34 judges including CJI)

📌 Number can be increased by Parliament.

🔹 Appointment of Judges
Appointed by the President
Based on Collegium system
Collegium includes:
CJI
4 senior-most judges

📌 Important for UPSC.

🔴 Qualifications of Judges
Citizen of India
At least:
5 years as High Court judge OR
10 years as advocate OR
Distinguished jurist
🔹 Tenure
Retires at 65 years
🔹 Jurisdiction of Supreme Court
1️⃣ Original Jurisdiction (Article 131)
Disputes between Centre & States
2️⃣ Appellate Jurisdiction
Appeals from High Courts
3️⃣ Advisory Jurisdiction (Article 143)
President seeks advice
4️⃣ Writ Jurisdiction (Article 32)
Protects Fundamental Rights
🔹 Judicial Review
Power to declare laws unconstitutional

📌 Basic structure doctrine (very important).

🔹 Types of Writs

Same as earlier:

Habeas Corpus
Mandamus
Certiorari
Prohibition
Quo Warranto
🔹 Important Points
Independent judiciary
Final interpreter of Constitution
Ensures rule of law
